  \label{Fig:tetra}
\end{figure}

To find the points with $\lambda({\boldsymbol{{k}}})=0$, we divide the reciprocal space into a set of space-filling tetrahedra. First, a regular rectangular grid is created with 8 neighboring grid points forming a cuboid. Then, each cuboid is further divided into 6 tetrahedra (\cf Fig.~\ref{Fig:tetra}a). As a next step, the roots of the eigenvalues $\lambda_i$ are searched for along the edges of a tetrahedron. Finally, the intersection area of the Fermi surface with the tetrahedron is determined. Three cases can be distinguished \cite{Bloechl:tetramethod}: a triangle (case I) or a quadrangle (case II, \cf Fig.~\ref{Fig:tetra}b) or no intersection area (case III). For sake of simplicity in a computer code, a quadrangle can be decomposed into two triangles and no distinction between the cases I and II has to be made in subsequent parts of the code.


We want to stress some computational aspects:
\begin{enumerate}

\item{The KKR matrix is in general non-hermitian and as a result the eigenvalues are complex numbers. The real and imaginary part of $\lambda_{o}$ do not necessarily vanish at the exact same $k$ point due to finite numerical cutoff parameters. We determine the root such, that the imaginary part vanishes and check whether also the real part is reasonably small. We usually achieve ${\ensuremath{\mathrm{Im}}} \lambda_{o} \sim 10^{-12}$ and ${\ensuremath{\mathrm{Re}}} \lambda_{o} \sim 10^{-5}$.}

\item{To find a root along an edge, we compute the eigenvalues at the start and end points of the edge and interpolate linearly in between. By doing so, we find an approximate Fermi-surface point where the linearly interpolated eigenvalue vanishes. However, the true intersection point of the Fermi surface with the edge will be somewhat different, and we refine the approximate $k$-point by applying a nested intervals method (false position method, \cf Ref.~\cite{numerical_recipies}). Usually, only three to five iterations are needed to ensure ${\ensuremath{\mathrm{Im}}} \lambda_{o}=0$ up to the precision stated above.}

\item{The order of the (complex valued) eigenvalues depends on the computer routine which is used to diagonalize the KKR matrix. Thus, when comparing the eigenvalues at two different ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$ points, $\lambda_i({\boldsymbol{{k}}}_1)$ and $\lambda_j({\boldsymbol{{k}}}_2)$, the connectivity ($i \leftrightarrow j$) that should correspond to the continuity of $\lambda_i({\boldsymbol{{k}}})$ is not known a-priori. As a result, it is not possible to interpolate the eigenvalues between discrete ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$ points. To resolve this issue, we use the fact that the coefficient vectors are (nearly) orthogonal to each other if they belong to different bands and the two ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$ points are not too far away from each other. We calculate the pairwise projections of these coefficient vectors, $p_{ij} = \bar{{\underline{{c}}}}_{i}({\boldsymbol{{k}}}_1)  \cdot {\underline{{c}}}_{j}({\boldsymbol{{k}}}_2)$. Here, $\bar{{\underline{{c}}}}_{i}({\boldsymbol{{k}}}_1)$ denotes a left eigenvector of ${\underline{\underline{{M}}}}({\boldsymbol{{k}}}_1)$, \ie

