In this way, the spin-matrix elements between Bloch states are expressed by a ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$-independent (but energy-dependent) matrix ${\boldsymbol{{{\underline{\underline{{\Sigma}}}}}}}$ and ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$-dependent eigenvectors ${\underline{{c}}}_{\nu}$. Algebraic manipulations involving linear combinations of $\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{\nu}$ (see, \eg, the Appendix) are thus merely transformed to manipulations containing the eigenvectors ${\underline{{c}}}_{\nu}$.



\subsection{Fermi-surface calculation\label{sec:KKR:fermisurface}}

In this section, we present details of our implementation of solving the KKR secular equation {(\ref{{KKR:secularequation_ref}})} to find the Fermi surface of a metal.

\subsubsection{Tetrahedron method}

To calculate the Fermi surface in practice, we fix the energy $E=E_\mathrm{F}$ in the secular equation {(\ref{{KKR:secularequation_ref}})} and drop it in our notation for simplicity. We scan the reciprocal space for a singular KKR matrix by reformulating the secular equation as an eigenvalue problem,

nexttext:
For a selected $i$, we find $p_{ij} \approx 1$ only for one $j \in \lbrace 1, \ldots, N \rbrace$, which determines the connection between the eigenvalues at ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}_1$ and ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}_2$.

If the system exhibits the aforementioned conjugation-degeneracy, each state is two-fold degenerate and, as a consequence, always two eigenvalues (say $\lambda_i$ and $\lambda_{i+1}$) are the same. Then, we only treat one of the two degenerate eigenvalues at ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}_{1}$ (\ie all $\lambda_{2i}$ for $i\in \lbrace 1, \ldots, N/2 \rbrace$), but still calculate the projections $p_{ij}$ for all $j \in \lbrace 1, \ldots, N\rbrace$ at ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}_{2}$. In the worst case, $\max_{j} p_{ij} \approx 0.5$ for the two $j$s that belong to the conjugation-degenerate pair and very small for the other $j$s.

We highlight that due to the correct connectivity of the eigenvalues, the method is capable of calculating crossings of Fermi-surface sheets correctly.}
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Visualization set}
At the end, the whole Fermi surface is represented as a collection of triangles from all tetrahedra. Evidently, neighboring tetrahedra share intersection points, and thus the number of \emph{distinct} ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$ points is much smaller than three times the number of triangles (typically by a factor of five to six for bulk crystals).
This set can still be utilized to visualize the Fermi surface and calculated properties on it, hence we call it \emph{visualization set}.

\subsubsection{Integration set\label{sec:KKR:integration_set}}
It may be required to further reduce the number of ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$ points on the Fermi surface. This is especially the case, when the quantity to be calculated is a function of two or more ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$ points. A prominent example is the scattering rate $P_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}} {\boldsymbol{{k'}}}}$ needed in the calculation of electron transport properties or spin and momentum relaxation times. We achieve a further reduction of the number of ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$ points by first merging all triangles that originate from a cuboid (remember that a regular rectangular mesh underlies the tetrahedra) into a set of triangles. Then, this whole set is represented by a single ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$ point, which is chosen to be the closest one to the center of the cuboid. A weight $S_{\boldsymbol{{k}}}$ of this representative ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$ point is given by the total area of the triangles in this set. If more than one Fermi-surface sheet intersects the cuboid, each sheet is represented by its own ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$ point and weight. All representative ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$ points form the so-called \emph{integration set}. It is not possible anymore to visualize this set, because the information about the explicit form of the Fermi surface is lost by concatenating it into the weights $S_{\boldsymbol{{k}}}$. However, the integration set is well suited to perform accurate Fermi-surface integrals.




\subsection{Fermi velocity\label{sec:KKR:fermivelocity}}

The Fermi velocity ${\boldsymbol{{v}}}_\mathrm{F}({\boldsymbol{{k}}}) = (\partial E/ \partial {\boldsymbol{{k}}}) \vert_{E=E_\mathrm{F}}$, where $E$ is the band energy under consideration, is often required for the evaluation of Fermi-surface integrals since it appears in the integration weight, ${\ensuremath{\mathrm{d}}}{S}/{\lvert {{\boldsymbol{{v}}}_\mathrm{F}({\boldsymbol{{k}}})} \rvert}$. 

In analogy to Gradhand \etal \cite{Gradhand.Berry.2011}, the Fermi velocity is calculated via the derivative of the KKR-matrix eigenvalues $\lambda_{o}$ with respect to ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$ and $E$,

prevtext:
The size $N=2 \, N_\mathrm{at} \, (\ell_\mathrm{max}+1)^2$ of the matrix ${\underline{\underline{{M}}}}$ is determined by the angular momentum cutoff $\ell_\mathrm{max}$, the number of atoms in the unit cell $N_\mathrm{at}$ and a factor 2 for spin. Evidently, for each matrix ${\underline{\underline{{M}}}}$, also $N$ eigenvalues and eigenvectors exist, which are labeled by $j$. A Fermi-surface point ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}_\mathrm{F}$ is found if at least one of these eigenvalues vanishes, $\lambda_{o}({\boldsymbol{{k}}}_\mathrm{F})=0$, and the corresponding eigenvector ${\underline{{c}}}_{o}({\boldsymbol{{k}}}_\mathrm{F})$ is proportional to the coefficient vector from {Eq.~{(\ref{{{KKR:secularequation}}})}} [a correct normalization of the wavefunction in {Eq.~{(\ref{{{KKR:wavefunction}}})}} has to be ensured]. If the corresponding state is $n$-fold degenerate, also $n$ eigenvalues vanish at the same band structure point $({\boldsymbol{{k}}}_\mathrm{F},E_\mathrm{F})$.

