\section*{Appendix: Linear combination of conjugation-degenerate states: discussion and physical interpretation}
\label{appendix:linear_combination}

Assuming that the crystal Hamiltonian is invariant under the action of 
the operators of space-inversion (parity) $P: \boldsymbol{\Psi}({\boldsymbol{{r}}})\rightarrow \boldsymbol{\Psi}(-{\boldsymbol{{r}}})$ and time-reversal $K: \boldsymbol{\Psi}({\boldsymbol{{r}}})\rightarrow i{\ensuremath{\sigma_y^\mathrm{P}}} \boldsymbol{\Psi}^*({\boldsymbol{{r}}})$, then for every Bloch eigenstate $\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}}$ there exists a conjugate partner eigenstate $PK\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}}$ that is degenerate at the same ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$, orthogonal to $\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}}$, and has the opposite spin expectation value \cite{Yafet.1963}. This is the case for the pair of Eqs.~(\ref{Eq:eyaf:wavefun1},\ref{Eq:eyaf:wavefun2}). Practically, time reversal symmetry means absence of external or internal magnetic fields in the crystal Hamiltonian.

In the case of conjugation degeneracy, and given a Bloch eigenfunction $\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}}$ of the crystal Hamiltonian, any linear combination $\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}}$ and $PK\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}}$ is obviously again a Bloch eigenfunction at the same ${\boldsymbol{{k}}}$. For the particular problem of spin relaxation, correspondence to experiment leads us to choose a linear combination that maximizes the spin expectation value along {\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}. For this we use the unitary transformation
\begin{eqnarray}
\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}} {\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}}^{+} &=& \cos\theta_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}}  \boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}} + \sin\theta_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}} e^{-i\phi_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}}} PK \boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}} \\
\label{Eq:eyaf:wavefun3}
\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}} {\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}}^{-} &=& -\sin\theta_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}} e^{i\phi_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}}} \boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}} + \cos\theta_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}} PK \boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}} 
\label{Eq:eyaf:wavefun4}
\end{eqnarray}
where two real parameters on the Bloch sphere, $\theta_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}}\in[0,\pi]$ and $\phi_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}}\in[0,2\pi]$, suffice for the definition of the normalized linear combinations up to an arbitrary global phase.
It is easy to see that $\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}} {\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}}^{-}=PK\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}} {\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}}^{+}$. Following Refs.~\cite{Elliott.1954,Fabian:HotSpots:1998} we then define appropriate $\theta_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}}$ and $\phi_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}}$ such that $S^{+}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}{\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}}:= \bra{\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}} {\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}}^{+}} \frac{\hbar}{2}{\ensuremath{\boldsymbol{\sigma}^\mathrm{P}}}\cdot{\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}\ket{\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}} {\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}}^{+}}\geq 0$ is maximal or equivalently  $S^{-}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}{\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}}:= \bra{\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}} {\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}}^{-}} \frac{\hbar}{2}{\ensuremath{\boldsymbol{\sigma}^\mathrm{P}}}\cdot{\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}\ket{\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}} {\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}}^{-}}=-S^{+}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}{\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}}\leq 0$ is minimal (maximal in absolute value). By demanding the derivatives with respect to $\theta$ and $\phi$ to vanish, we obtain a maximal $S^{+}_{{\boldsymbol{{k}}}{\ensuremath{{\hat{{s}}}}}}$ under the condition:
